INSERT INTO questions (subject, topic, difficulty, question_text, choices, correct_answer, explanation, exam_type) VALUES
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','According to Piaget, which stage is characterized by abstract thinking and hypothetical reasoning?','[{"key":"A","text":"Sensorimotor"},{"key":"B","text":"Preoperational"},{"key":"C","text":"Concrete Operational"},{"key":"D","text":"Formal Operational"}]','D','The Formal Operational stage (12+ years) is marked by abstract thought, hypothetical reasoning, and logical deduction.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Vygotsky''s Zone of Proximal Development (ZPD) refers to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Tasks a child can do independently"},{"key":"B","text":"Tasks too difficult even with help"},{"key":"C","text":"The gap between what a child can do alone and with guidance"},{"key":"D","text":"The child''s comfort zone in learning"}]','C','ZPD is the distance between actual development (independent) and potential development (with skilled guidance).','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Erik Erikson''s stage for adolescents (12–18 years) is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Industry vs. Inferiority"},{"key":"B","text":"Identity vs. Role Confusion"},{"key":"C","text":"Intimacy vs. Isolation"},{"key":"D","text":"Initiative vs. Guilt"}]','B','Erikson''s fifth stage involves adolescents forming a personal identity; failure leads to role confusion.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Which Piagetian concept refers to a child''s inability to see things from another person''s perspective?','[{"key":"A","text":"Conservation"},{"key":"B","text":"Centration"},{"key":"C","text":"Egocentrism"},{"key":"D","text":"Animism"}]','C','Egocentrism in the preoperational stage means the child cannot take another''s viewpoint.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Object permanence — understanding that objects exist even when out of sight — develops in Piaget''s:','[{"key":"A","text":"Sensorimotor stage"},{"key":"B","text":"Preoperational stage"},{"key":"C","text":"Concrete Operational stage"},{"key":"D","text":"Formal Operational stage"}]','A','Object permanence emerges around 8–12 months during the Sensorimotor stage.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Scaffolding, as used in Vygotsky''s theory, means:','[{"key":"A","text":"Punishing incorrect responses"},{"key":"B","text":"Providing temporary support to help a learner accomplish a task"},{"key":"C","text":"Letting children learn entirely on their own"},{"key":"D","text":"Grouping students by ability"}]','B','Scaffolding is temporary assistance given by a more capable person, gradually withdrawn as the learner gains competence.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','hard','Kohlberg''s postconventional level of moral development includes which stage?','[{"key":"A","text":"Punishment and obedience"},{"key":"B","text":"Instrumental purpose"},{"key":"C","text":"Social contract and universal ethical principles"},{"key":"D","text":"Good boy/good girl orientation"}]','C','Postconventional morality involves abstract principles of justice and human rights beyond social rules.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Which theorist proposed the concept of multiple intelligences?','[{"key":"A","text":"Jean Piaget"},{"key":"B","text":"Howard Gardner"},{"key":"C","text":"Lev Vygotsky"},{"key":"D","text":"Erik Erikson"}]','B','Howard Gardner proposed 8 intelligences: linguistic, logical-mathematical, spatial, musical, bodily-kinesthetic, interpersonal, intrapersonal, and naturalist.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Bronfenbrenner''s microsystem refers to:','[{"key":"A","text":"The broader cultural context"},{"key":"B","text":"Interactions between two settings the child is in"},{"key":"C","text":"The immediate environment (family, school, peers)"},{"key":"D","text":"Historical and time-based influences"}]','C','The microsystem is the immediate setting where the child directly interacts, such as home and school.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','In Piaget''s theory, assimilation means:','[{"key":"A","text":"Changing existing schemas to fit new information"},{"key":"B","text":"Integrating new information into existing schemas"},{"key":"C","text":"The balance between assimilation and accommodation"},{"key":"D","text":"Creating entirely new schemas"}]','B','Assimilation is incorporating new experiences into existing mental frameworks without changing them.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Erikson''s stage for school-age children (6–12) is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Initiative vs. Guilt"},{"key":"B","text":"Trust vs. Mistrust"},{"key":"C","text":"Industry vs. Inferiority"},{"key":"D","text":"Autonomy vs. Shame"}]','C','School-age children develop competence through learning; failure leads to feelings of inferiority.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','A child who believes the moon follows them as they walk is demonstrating:','[{"key":"A","text":"Animism"},{"key":"B","text":"Egocentrism"},{"key":"C","text":"Conservation"},{"key":"D","text":"Centration"}]','B','Egocentrism causes the child to believe the world revolves around them, including the moon "following" them.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Conservation, the understanding that quantity remains the same despite changes in shape, develops in:','[{"key":"A","text":"Sensorimotor stage"},{"key":"B","text":"Preoperational stage"},{"key":"C","text":"Concrete Operational stage"},{"key":"D","text":"Formal Operational stage"}]','C','Concrete Operational children (7–11) can understand conservation of number, mass, and volume.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Which stage of Erikson involves the crisis of "Trust vs. Mistrust"?','[{"key":"A","text":"Toddlerhood"},{"key":"B","text":"Infancy (0–1 year)"},{"key":"C","text":"Preschool"},{"key":"D","text":"School age"}]','B','The first stage of Erikson''s theory occurs in infancy; consistent caregiving builds trust.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','hard','Kohlberg''s Stage 3 (Good Boy/Good Girl orientation) belongs to which level?','[{"key":"A","text":"Preconventional"},{"key":"B","text":"Conventional"},{"key":"C","text":"Postconventional"},{"key":"D","text":"Pre-moral"}]','B','Stage 3 is part of the Conventional level where moral decisions are based on social approval.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','A teacher who adapts instruction to a student''s ZPD is applying:','[{"key":"A","text":"Behaviorism"},{"key":"B","text":"Maturation theory"},{"key":"C","text":"Vygotsky''s sociocultural theory"},{"key":"D","text":"Freud''s psychoanalysis"}]','C','Instructing within the ZPD with scaffolding is a direct application of Vygotsky''s theory.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Gardner''s intelligence related to understanding others is called:','[{"key":"A","text":"Intrapersonal"},{"key":"B","text":"Interpersonal"},{"key":"C","text":"Linguistic"},{"key":"D","text":"Spatial"}]','B','Interpersonal intelligence involves understanding and interacting effectively with others.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Which of Bronfenbrenner''s systems involves interactions between two environments a child participates in?','[{"key":"A","text":"Microsystem"},{"key":"B","text":"Mesosystem"},{"key":"C","text":"Exosystem"},{"key":"D","text":"Macrosystem"}]','B','The mesosystem includes the connections between two microsystems, such as home-school relationships.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','hard','Accommodation in Piaget''s theory occurs when:','[{"key":"A","text":"A child fits new information into an old schema"},{"key":"B","text":"A child modifies an existing schema to fit new information"},{"key":"C","text":"Equilibrium is achieved"},{"key":"D","text":"A child ignores conflicting information"}]','B','Accommodation involves changing existing schemas when new information cannot be assimilated.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','A child in the preoperational stage who believes clouds feel sad is demonstrating:','[{"key":"A","text":"Egocentrism"},{"key":"B","text":"Centration"},{"key":"C","text":"Animism"},{"key":"D","text":"Irreversibility"}]','C','Animism is the belief that inanimate objects have life and feelings.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Maslow''s hierarchy places which need at the top?','[{"key":"A","text":"Safety needs"},{"key":"B","text":"Esteem needs"},{"key":"C","text":"Self-actualization"},{"key":"D","text":"Physiological needs"}]','C','Self-actualization — reaching one''s full potential — is at the pinnacle of Maslow''s hierarchy.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Which Erikson stage involves the crisis experienced by young adults (19–40)?','[{"key":"A","text":"Identity vs. Role Confusion"},{"key":"B","text":"Intimacy vs. Isolation"},{"key":"C","text":"Generativity vs. Stagnation"},{"key":"D","text":"Ego Integrity vs. Despair"}]','B','Young adults face the challenge of forming intimate relationships; failure leads to isolation.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','The "private speech" children use while solving problems is associated with:','[{"key":"A","text":"Piaget''s egocentrism"},{"key":"B","text":"Vygotsky''s inner speech development"},{"key":"C","text":"Erikson''s initiative stage"},{"key":"D","text":"Kohlberg''s moral reasoning"}]','B','Vygotsky viewed private speech as a self-regulatory tool that eventually becomes internalized thought.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','hard','In Bronfenbrenner''s model, the chronosystem refers to:','[{"key":"A","text":"The cultural values of society"},{"key":"B","text":"Settings the child is not directly involved in"},{"key":"C","text":"Changes over time including historical events"},{"key":"D","text":"Direct interactions with family"}]','C','The chronosystem encompasses the dimension of time — changes in the child and environment over time.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Which stage of Piaget involves learning through senses and motor actions (birth to 2 years)?','[{"key":"A","text":"Preoperational"},{"key":"B","text":"Concrete Operational"},{"key":"C","text":"Formal Operational"},{"key":"D","text":"Sensorimotor"}]','D','The Sensorimotor stage involves learning through direct sensory experience and motor actions.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','A student who studies hard to win a scholarship (external reward) is motivated by:','[{"key":"A","text":"Intrinsic motivation"},{"key":"B","text":"Self-actualization"},{"key":"C","text":"Extrinsic motivation"},{"key":"D","text":"Cognitive dissonance"}]','C','Extrinsic motivation is driven by external rewards such as money, grades, or recognition.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','The concept of "nature vs. nurture" in development refers to:','[{"key":"A","text":"Teachers vs. parents"},{"key":"B","text":"Genetics vs. environment"},{"key":"C","text":"School vs. home"},{"key":"D","text":"Intelligence vs. emotion"}]','B','The nature-nurture debate concerns the relative contributions of genetic inheritance and environmental experience.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','hard','According to Kohlberg, most adults operate at which level of moral development?','[{"key":"A","text":"Preconventional"},{"key":"B","text":"Postconventional"},{"key":"C","text":"Conventional"},{"key":"D","text":"Transitional"}]','C','Research shows most adults reason at the conventional level, following social rules and laws.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Gardner''s intelligence involving sensitivity to music and rhythm is:','[{"key":"A","text":"Spatial"},{"key":"B","text":"Bodily-kinesthetic"},{"key":"C","text":"Linguistic"},{"key":"D","text":"Musical"}]','D','Musical intelligence involves skill in rhythm, pitch, melody, and musical pattern recognition.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Which theorist emphasized the role of social interaction and culture in cognitive development?','[{"key":"A","text":"Jean Piaget"},{"key":"B","text":"B.F. Skinner"},{"key":"C","text":"Lev Vygotsky"},{"key":"D","text":"Sigmund Freud"}]','C','Vygotsky''s sociocultural theory emphasizes that learning is a social process mediated by culture and language.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Equilibration in Piaget''s theory is:','[{"key":"A","text":"The process of forgetting old information"},{"key":"B","text":"The drive to balance assimilation and accommodation"},{"key":"C","text":"A type of memory consolidation"},{"key":"D","text":"The transition from one stage to another"}]','B','Equilibration is the self-regulatory mechanism that drives cognitive development by balancing assimilation and accommodation.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','Which of the following describes a "scheme" in Piaget''s theory?','[{"key":"A","text":"A classroom seating plan"},{"key":"B","text":"A mental framework for organizing information"},{"key":"C","text":"A type of behavioral reinforcement"},{"key":"D","text":"A student''s learning style"}]','B','Schemas (schemes) are cognitive structures used to organize and interpret information about the world.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Erikson''s stage of "Initiative vs. Guilt" occurs during:','[{"key":"A","text":"Infancy"},{"key":"B","text":"School age"},{"key":"C","text":"Preschool (3–6 years)"},{"key":"D","text":"Adolescence"}]','C','Preschoolers develop initiative through play; excessive criticism leads to guilt.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','hard','A child who cannot understand that rolling a ball of clay into a snake doesn''t change its mass lacks:','[{"key":"A","text":"Object permanence"},{"key":"B","text":"Conservation"},{"key":"C","text":"Reversibility"},{"key":"D","text":"Seriation"}]','B','Conservation is the understanding that properties like mass, volume, and number remain constant despite physical changes.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','Bowlby''s attachment theory states that:','[{"key":"A","text":"Children learn through observation"},{"key":"B","text":"Early emotional bonds with caregivers shape future relationships"},{"key":"C","text":"Intelligence is genetically determined"},{"key":"D","text":"Play is the primary mode of learning"}]','B','Bowlby proposed that secure early attachment to caregivers provides a foundation for healthy emotional development.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','easy','According to Maslow, which needs must be met first before higher needs can be pursued?','[{"key":"A","text":"Esteem needs"},{"key":"B","text":"Love and belonging"},{"key":"C","text":"Physiological needs"},{"key":"D","text":"Safety needs"}]','C','Physiological needs (food, water, shelter) are at the base of Maslow''s hierarchy and must be satisfied first.','both'),
('Professional Education','Child and Adolescent Development','medium','A teenager questioning "Who am I?" is experiencing Erikson''s:','[{"key":"A","text":"Industry vs. Inferiority"},{"key":"B","text":"Identity vs. Role Confusion"},{"key":"C","text":"Autonomy vs. Shame"},{"key":"D","text":"Intimacy vs. Isolation"}]','B','The identity crisis of adolescence involves exploring values, beliefs, and goals to form a coherent sense of self.','both');
